## Why This Is Asked
Assesses ability to design cross-protocol schema alignment and implement practical versioning strategies.

## Key Concepts
- Multi-protocol schema mapping from canonical model
- Unified internal service layer with protocol adapters
- Consistent versioning across all protocols
- Contract validation and routing patterns

## Code Example

```javascript
// Canonical model adapter
function toInternalBook(restInput) {
  return {
    id: restInput.id || generateId(),
    title: restInput.title,
    author: restInput.author,
    stock: restInput.stock || 0
  };
}

// Protocol-agnostic service layer
const bookService = {
  async getBook(id) {
    return await database.books.findById(id);
  },
  async createBook(bookData) {
    const internalBook = toInternalBook(bookData);
    return await database.books.create(internalBook);
  }
};

// Protocol adapters
const restAdapter = {
  getBook: async (req, res) => {
    const book = await bookService.getBook(req.params.id);
    res.json(book);
  },
  createBook: async (req, res) => {
    const book = await bookService.createBook(req.body);
    res.status(201).json(book);
  }
};

// GraphQL schema
type Book {
  id: ID!
  title: String!
  author: String!
  stock: Int!
}

type Query {
  getBook(id: ID!): Book
}

type Mutation {
  addBook(title: String!, author: String!, stock: Int): Book
}

// gRPC service definition
service BookService {
  rpc GetBook(GetBookRequest) returns (Book);
  rpc CreateBook(CreateBookRequest) returns (Book);
}

// Versioning patterns
// REST: /api/v1/books
// GraphQL: Use @deprecated directive for v2 changes
// gRPC: package v1.bookservice;
```

## Implementation Strategy
1. Define canonical domain model first
2. Create protocol-specific schemas that map to the canonical model
3. Implement adapter layer for request/response transformation
4. Build unified service layer with business logic
5. Apply consistent versioning strategy across all protocols

## Why This Is Asked

Tests practical design for a multi-protocol, multi-tenant API gateway including per-tenant OpenAPI contracts, quota enforcement, and safe schema migrations. Requires concrete patterns, data modeling, and a touch of operational realism.

## Key Concepts

- Multi-protocol gateways (REST, GraphQL, gRPC)
- Per-tenant OpenAPI contracts and dynamic loading
- Request normalization and cross-channel tracing
- Per-tenant rate limiting and isolation
- Versioned contract migrations and safe schema evolution
- Observability and error handling across protocols

## Code Example

```javascript
// Minimal REST-to-GraphQL adapter sketch
class RestToGraphQLAdapter {
  constructor(gqlClient) { this.gqlClient = gqlClient; }
  async route(req) {
    // Map REST path to GraphQL query, using tenant from headers
    const tenant = req.headers["x-tenant-id"];
    const { id } = req.params;
    const query = `query GetItem($id: ID!) { item(id: $id) { id, name, stock } }`;
    const res = await this.gqlClient.request(query, { id, tenant });
    return { status: 200, body: res.data.item };
  }
}
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you test per-tenant contract migrations in production without affecting others?
- What strategies ensure schema migrations stay backward-compatible across tenants?

## Performance Characteristics

**REST**: HTTP/1.1 overhead ~1KB per request, limited to one request per connection. Best for CRUD operations with ~95% cacheability.

**GraphQL**: Single endpoint reduces network overhead, but query complexity can cause N+1 problems. Apollo Engine shows 30-40% payload reduction vs REST.

**gRPC**: HTTP/2 multiplexing enables concurrent streams. Protocol Buffers reduce payload size by 60-80% vs JSON.

## Use Case Scenarios

```typescript
// REST - Public API
GET /api/users/123/posts

// GraphQL - Mobile app with data requirements
query GetUserPosts($userId: ID!) {
  user(id: $userId) {
    name
    posts(first: 10) {
      title
      comments(count: 3)
    }
  }
}

// gRPC - Internal microservice
service UserService {
  rpc GetUser(GetUserRequest) returns (UserResponse);
}
```

## Error Handling & Authentication

- **REST**: HTTP status codes (200, 404, 500) + JWT/OAuth2
- **GraphQL**: Single 200 response with error payload + JWT
- **gRPC**: Status codes (OK, NOT_FOUND, INTERNAL) + SSL/TLS with token-based auth

## Real-World Applications

- Netflix: REST for public APIs, gRPC for internal services
- GitHub: GraphQL v4 API (95% faster than REST v3)
- Uber: gRPC for microservices communication (30% latency reduction)

## Why This Is Asked
This evaluates your understanding of API design patterns, code reuse principles, and performance optimization across different API paradigms—critical skills for building scalable microservice architectures.

## Expected Answer
Strong candidates should discuss: a shared business logic layer, separate API adapters for REST and GraphQL, GraphQL data loaders for query batching, REST response caching mechanisms, and database query optimization tailored to each API type's access patterns.

## Code Example
```typescript
// Shared service layer
class UserService {
  async getUser(id: string) {
    return db.user.findUnique({ where: { id } });
  }
}

// GraphQL resolver with data loader
const userResolver = {
  user: async (_, { id }, { loaders }) => {
    return loaders.user.load(id);
  }
};
```

## Why This Is Asked
This tests practical ability to integrate REST, GraphQL, and gRPC behind a unified gateway, including automated OpenAPI generation and consistent authentication patterns.

## Key Concepts
- grpc-gateway for REST-to-gRPC translation
- OpenAPI generation from protobuf definitions
- JWT propagation through gRPC metadata
- Protocol buffer annotations for REST/GraphQL binding

## Code Example
```go
// REST to gRPC translation with grpc-gateway
func (s *server) CreateUser(ctx context.Context, req *pb.CreateUserRequest) (*pb.User, error) {
    // Forward to internal gRPC service
    return s.userService.CreateUser(ctx, req)
}

// Gateway setup with JWT propagation
func main() {
    mux := runtime.NewServeMux(
        runtime.WithIncomingHeaderMatcher(func(key string) (string, bool) {
            return key, strings.ToLower(key) == "authorization"
        }),
    )

    // Register gRPC services
    pb.RegisterUserServiceHandlerFromEndpoint(ctx, mux, "localhost:9090", []grpc.DialOption{
        grpc.WithInsecure(),
    })

    // GraphQL handler
    gqlHandler := handler.New(graphql.NewSchema())

    // Combine routers
    router := gin.Default()
    router.Any("/api/v1/*path", gin.WrapH(mux))
    router.POST("/graphql", gin.WrapH(gqlHandler))
}
```

