## Why This Is Asked

This tests ability to design a lightweight, beginner-auth flow that handles multiple IdP formats, with per-tenant audience, scope enforcement, and a simple revocation mechanism—without a heavy gateway.

## Key Concepts

- Multi-IdP token translation
- Tenant-scoped audience (aud) and per-resource scopes
- TTL revocation cache (jti)
- Middleware gate for downstream access

## Code Example

```javascript
// Issuance snippet
function issueInternalToken(sub, tenant, scope){
  const payload = {sub, tenant, scope, aud: `${tenant}-resources`, iat: now(), exp: now()+600, jti: uuid()}
  return signJWT(payload)
}
```

```javascript
// Revocation check
function isRevoked(jti){ return cache.get(jti) !== undefined }
```

```javascript
// Route guard
function authorize(req){ const t = verifyJWT(req.header('Authorization'));
  return t && t.aud === `${t.tenant}-resources` && t.scope.includes('read:resources')
}
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you test token rotation and clock skew?
- How would you extend to token introspection without breaking existing IdPs?

## Why This Is Asked
Real-world setups use multiple IdPs; token replay and cross-provider binding are critical issues.

## Key Concepts
- JWKS caching and key rotation per provider
- Replay protection with jti in distributed cache
- Token binding via CNF and mTLS
- Revocation propagation and token lifecycle

## Code Example
```javascript
function verifyJwt(token, provider) {
  const key = getJwksKey(provider, token.kid);
  const payload = jwtVerify(token, key);
  if (Date.now() >= payload.exp * 1000) throw new Error('expired');
  if (redis.exists(`jti:${payload.jti}`)) throw new Error('replay');
  redis.set(`jti:${payload.jti}`, 1, 'EX', payload.exp - now);
  return payload;
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you handle JWKS rotation events?
- How would you monitor and debug cross-provider revocation flows?

## Why This Is Asked

Explores bridging multi‑IdP authentication (OIDC, SAML) into a unified JWT path for a service mesh, emphasizing token binding, replay protection, PKCE, and cross‑region revocation.

## Key Concepts

- Token binding to device fingerprint
- SAML/OIDC to JWT bridging
- Token exchange (RFC 8693)
- Refresh token rotation
- Global revocation and JWKS rotation

## Code Example

```javascript
function validateToken(token, expectedAud) {
  const payload = parseJwt(token);
  if (payload.iss !== "https://idp.example.com") return false;
  if (!payload.aud.includes(expectedAud)) return false;
  if (Date.now() >= payload.exp * 1000) return false;
  return verifyJwt(token, payload.kid);
}
```

